{          Positive Inferences          }
^-|cp||fp||CS||AT|^c@2^Y@3Positive inferences are straight forward. You can determine many facts about the other hands by the bidding and card play. Next, are some examples. |
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

1. Your opponent opens 1H/1S. Therefore, he or she must have at least five spades/hearts. |
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|

2. Similarly, your opponent has pre-empted. If the opening bid was a Weak-2, the opener has a six-card suit. If the opening bid was at the three level, the opener has a seven-card suit (you already know about more than half the cards in his/her hand!).|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT| 

3. Declarer opens 1NT. The hand cannot contain more than one doubleton (and therefore no 6-card suit), and no singletons or voids. In fact, declarer's distribution should either be 4-3-3-3, 4-4-3-2, or 5-3-3-2. |
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT|

