qx|A5,Negative inferences|HT|d|FP|2|cs|1|CP|4|at|^-
{          Negative Inferences          }
^-|cp||fp||CS||AT|^c@2^Y@3Negative inferences are similar to the famous mystery story in which Sherlock Holmes solves the crime because the dog did not bark. You can often determine what someone has by what they did not do. For example.|
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


AT|

1. Declarer opened 1C/1D. It is almost certain that he/she does not have a five-card major. |
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


AT|

2. You open 1H and partner bids 1NT. Partner has neither three hearts (would have raised to 2H) nor four spades (would have bid 1S). |
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


AT|

3. Declarer opens 1C, responder bids 1H, opener rebids 1NT. Since the rebid was neither 1S nor 2H, declarer has at most 3 spades and 3 hearts. Declarer also has at least four clubs--if he/she only had three clubs, the hand must contain four diamonds, and therefore 1D would have been the opening bid. |
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


AT|

Look at all the information that can be gleaned from such a common auction! |
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


AT|

4. Partner leads the two of a suit against no-trump, showing four. Partner does not have another 5-card suit (unless it was bid by the opponents). |
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


AT|

5. You bid a suit and partner does not lead your suit--the opening lead is a low card in another suit. Partner better have a void! |
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


AT|

As defender, you can usually determine declarer's distribution within a card or two by the time trumps are drawn. If you lead a side suit and more than one round is played, you often can determine the distribution of that suit. Similarly, once trumps are drawn, you know the trump distribution. |
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


