{          Negative Inferences          }
^-|cp||fp||CS||AT|^c@2^Y@3Finally, declarer has bid, so you have additional information about the hand. I recommend that you develop the habit of counting declarer's hand on every deal; it should become automatic after a while.|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


AT|

One technique that helped me develop my counting skills was to try and count the hand when I was dummy. This can be difficult, because you can only see 13 cards, not 26. However, as dummy you have little else to do anyway, and it makes your counting skills that much sharper. This is hard to do on BBO, since by default you can see all four hands as dummy. But you can do this in live bridge. |
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


AT|

Before we get to examples, I want to discuss one fairly easy counting technique. If you learn nothing else from this lesson, I hope you will try and use this technique. The technique has to do with counting trumps and other long suits you may have as declarer. |
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


AT|

Many people try to count trumps by figuring out how many have been played. So, if they play one round, and everyone follows they say "four have been played." Then if they play another round, and say one defender doesn't follow, they think "seven have been played." But that can get very complicated, particularly if you as declarer or one of the defenders has ruffed a trick.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


AT|

A much easier way to keep track of trumps, or any long suit, is to just remember how many are out in the defenders hand. So, if you start with an 8-card fit, then there are five out in the two defensive hands. If you play one round, and both follow, then just remember there are three out. It is much easier to do it this way, as you are keeping track of fewer cards and numbers. You simply remember how many are out. Let me load an example hand to show you.|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


AT|

Next, let's look at a hand to see how we can make use of both positive and negative inferences.  |
